@ about page
@about.heading: about
@about.h_project: Project
@about.h_feedback: Feedback
@about.h_people: People
@about.h_support: Support
@about.role_director: Director
@about.role_tech_director: Technical Director
@about.role_ra: Research Assistant
@about.project: This project aims—from an interdisciplinary perspective—to fill a large gap in research on minority Francophone community experience in British Columbia. By building bridges between research institutions, cultural organizations, artists, and Francophone schools, it seeks to foster a culture of community resilience through creative engagement with Francophone music. Research on music in socio-cultural context has shown that participatory music, that is, a musical event in which the audience takes an active part in music making, contributes to social cohesion, identity formation, and well-being. Furthermore, research has shown that music-based interventions contribute significantly to language development. This project proposes to harness innovative music technology to develop open-access, digital resources that have the potential to enhance intergenerational language transfer, music education, and community-based music making. Research activities include ethnographic research, development of music-based pedagogical interventions, and a series of workshops highlighting the ethnic diversity of Francophone musical practices (planned for 2027).
@about.feedback: Do you see a mistake in a score? Do you disagree with our editorial choices? Would you like a particular score to be texted? <a href="mailto:The1520sProject@gmail.com">Let us know</a>.
@about.support: This project has been generously supported by <a href="https://disa.arts.ubc.ca/" target="_blank">UBC Digital Scholarship in the Arts</a> and by <a href="https://languagesciences.ubc.ca/" target="_blank">UBC Language Sciences</a> through a Knowledge Mobilization and Dissemination Grant, and by the <a href="https://www.ccarh.org/" target="_blank">Stanford Center for Computer Assisted Research in the Humanities</a>.
@about.bio_sam: TBC
@about.bio_eve: I am an Associate Professor in music theory at the School of Music of the University of British Columbia, where I teach courses on compositional practice in the 18th- and 19th-century, techniques of graphic linear analysis, music psychology, Francophone music, and digital technology in music research and creation. My research has been presented at interdisciplinary conferences in North America, Europe, and the Middle East, and published in Music Perception, Empirical Musicology Review, Action, Perception &amp; Cognition, and the Journal of New Music Research. My current projects focus on empirical aesthetics, rhythmic polyphony, and folk music of French-Canada, combining methods of close study, computer-aided musicology, and behavioural experimentation.
@about.bio_craig: Craig Sapp is a world expert in computer-based musical analysis who develops transformative digital-humanities projects in collaboration with colleagues and students. As consulting professor at Stanford University, Sapp teaches courses in computational music theory and digital musicology. He serves as technical director of not only the <a href="https://josquin.stanford.edu" target="_blank">Josquin Research Project</a>, but also the NEH-funded <a href="https://www.tassomusic.org/" target="_blank">Tasso in Music Project</a>, and as technical lead for the <a href="https://chopin.musicsources.pl/en/" target="_blank">Chopin Heritage in Open Access project</a> (2016–20), the <a href="https://polish.musicsources.pl/pl" target="_blank">Polish Music in Open Access project</a> (2019–22), and the <a href="https://polyrhythm.humdrum.org" target="_blank">Polyrhythm Project</a> (2018–present). He served as a consultant for the <a href="https://gaspar-van-weerbeke.eu" target="_blank">Gaspar Online Edition</a> (2021–22).
@about.bio_isaac: Isaac is a UBC Computer Science student (BCS, 2027) with a BMus (2025) in Organ and Ancient Mediterranean and Near Eastern Studies. He has been part of the project since summer 2025 doing music encoding, and now <a href="https://github.com/zaxophone" target="_blank">technical work</a> on the website and other areas. He is also an organist and children's choir director for Holy Family Parish (FSSP).

@ documentation page
@doc.heading: documentation
@doc.h_procedure: Encoding Procedure
@doc.h_general: General Encoding
@doc.h_text: Text Encoding
@doc.h_music: Music Encoding
@doc.h_text_analysis: Text Analysis
@doc.h_additional: Additional Notes
@doc.h_formatting: Formatting
@doc.intro: This repository contains Francophone folk songs encoded as <strong>Humdrum <code>**kern</code></strong> files. Encoding is <em>diplomatic</em> and includes the musical score, poetic text, phonemes, and rhyme analysis.
@doc.content_general: <ol>
<li><p><strong>Record comments</strong> (preceding each song). Example from "O Canada!" (note the space after each colon); for page numbers, add "t" for songs that end on a second page followed by another song on the same page; add "b" for songs preceded by the end of another song on the same page.</p>
<pre><code>!!!id: BC001
!!!page: 4-5
!!!COM: Lavallée, Calixa
!!!LYR: Routhier, juge A.-B.
!!!PTL@@FR: Les 100 plus belles chansons
!!!OTL@@FR: O Canada, terre de nos aïeux
!!!PUB: La Bonne Chanson, inc.
!!!YEM: On ne peut reproduire, enregistrer ou diffuser en tout ou en partie le présent ouvrage, sous quelque procédé que ce soit, électronique, mécanique, photographique, sonore, magnétique ou autre, sans avoir obtenu au préalable l'autorisation écrite de l'éditrice.
!!!PDT: 2011
!!!SMA: 2012 Bibliothèque nationale du Québec; Biblothèque nationale du Canada
!!!AGN-Laforte: Chanson strophique (sans refrain), 8:10(4+6)
!!!AGN-type: hymne national
!!!AGN-rime: mixte, aabcbcbc</code></pre>
<p>For a list of record comment types, consult: <a href="https://www.humdrum.org/reference-records">https://www.humdrum.org/reference-records</a></p></li>
<li><p><strong>Spine structure</strong>:</p>
<ul><li>Melody (Spine 1): <code>*</code></li>
<li>Verse 1 (Spine 2): <code>*v:1</code></li>
<li>Verse 2 (Spine 3): <code>*v:2</code></li></ul></li>
<li><p><strong>To add an empty spine</strong> after the first is completed:</p>
<pre><code>extract -s 1-$,0</code></pre></li>
<li><p><strong>Preserve visual layout</strong> of original:</p>
<ul><li>Insert <code>!!LO:PB:g=original</code> above the measure that appears on the next system.</li>
<li>Use the alignment button to preserve layout.</li>
<li>For longer songs (&gt;4 systems), switch to "continuous" view on the toolbar.</li></ul></li>
<li><p><strong>Add editorial comments</strong> (e.g., pitch variants). Place above the relevant line with a <code>!</code>:</p>
<pre><code>!pitch variant:b</code></pre>
<p>Ensure each spine on the same row includes an exclamation mark.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Encoding completion info</strong>. Use "First Last" for name and "year/mm/dd" for date:</p>
<pre><code>!!!EED: Ève Poudrier
!!!EEV: 2025/05/06</code></pre></li>
<li><p><strong>Encoding editorial comments</strong>:</p>
<pre><code>!!!RNB (Representation note) — encode any modifications to the score representation, e.g. replacing dal segno symbols by repeats.
!!!RWG (Representation warning) — point out unusual representations in the original score.</code></pre></li>
</ol>
@doc.content_text: <ol>
<li><p><strong>Syllabification</strong>: Prefix all middle and end syllables with a hyphen (<code>-</code>).</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Line numbering</strong> (across all verses): Use <code>*pline:n</code> (e.g., <code>*pline:1</code>). Refrains use <code>*pline:R1</code>, <code>*pline:R2</code>, etc.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Refrain formatting</strong> (italics): Encode with <code>*refrain</code> and <code>*italic</code> before the first refrain syllable, and <code>*Xitalic</code> and <code>*Xrefrain</code> after the last. Refrains repeated in alternation with verses are encoded once and marked with <code>*&gt;Refrain</code>. <em>Note: automatic italics via <code>*refrain</code> to be added.</em></p></li>
<li><p><strong>Joint syllables</strong>: Notes set with two or more joined syllables (e.g., "il y a" as "ya") should be set with a space to add a slur joining the syllables.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Elisions</strong>: Final "e" (/ə/) elided without an apostrophe in the original should be put in square brackets, e.g. "dans[e]". Use the same procedure for plural endings "es" and "ent" pronounced as /ə/.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Repetitions</strong>: Full line repetitions are suffixed "r" (e.g., <code>*pline:1r</code>). Partial line repetitions:</p>
<pre><code>*pline:1a    ← start
*pline:1c    ← middle
*pline:1b    ← end</code></pre>
<p>Single-word repetitions: surround with <code>*bis</code> … <code>*Xbis</code>.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Text analysis</strong>: Mark line endings with three interpretations:</p>
<pre><code>*rp:ø
*rf:jø
*rs:a</code></pre>
<table><thead><tr><th>interpretation</th><th>meaning</th><th>example</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><code>rp</code></td><td>phoneme</td><td>vowel of rhyme</td></tr>
<tr><td><code>rf</code></td><td>phoneme group</td><td>full rhyme</td></tr>
<tr><td><code>rs</code></td><td>structure label</td><td>lowercase letter</td></tr>
</tbody></table>
<p>When the same vowel appears with different consonants, append a number:</p>
<table><thead><tr><th>ending</th><th>rhyme vowel</th><th>full rhyme</th><th>label</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>vent</td><td><code>*rp:ɑ̃</code></td><td><code>*rf:vɑ̃</code></td><td><code>*rs:a1</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>gens</td><td><code>*rp:ɑ̃</code></td><td><code>*rf:ʒɑ̃</code></td><td><code>*rs:a2</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>ange</td><td><code>*rp:ɑ̃</code></td><td><code>*rf:ɑ̃ʒ,ə</code></td><td><code>*rs:a3</code></td></tr>
</tbody></table>
<p>Mute "e" are added to the full rhyme, set apart by a comma.</p></li>
</ol>
@doc.content_music: <ol>
<li><p><strong>Melodic grouping</strong> (segmentation levels):</p>
<ul><li>First: <code>{...}</code></li>
<li>Second: <code>{{...}}</code></li>
<li>Third: <code>{{{...}}}</code></li></ul></li>
<li><p><strong>Segmentation guidance</strong>:</p>
<ul><li>Segments = short units, often bounded by rests.</li>
<li>Phrases = melodic contour or textual line ends.</li>
<li>Periods = ≥2 phrases with cadences and structural relation.</li></ul></li>
<li><p><strong>Tempo marking</strong>: Insert under first measure:</p>
<pre><code>!!LO:TX:a:t=Majestueux et résolu</code></pre></li>
<li><p><strong>Accidentals</strong>: To hide an accidental, add "y".</p></li>
</ol>
@doc.content_text_analysis: <ol>
<li><p><strong>Rhyme marking</strong> (after final word of each line):</p>
<ul><li>Phoneme (assonance): <code>*rp:ø</code></li>
<li>Full rhyme group: <code>*rf:yø</code></li>
<li>Structure label: <code>*rs:a</code>, <code>*rs:b</code>, …</li></ul>
<blockquote><p>Note: Kern does not differentiate /a/ sounds (e.g., "orage" vs. "naufrage"). Add an editorial comment for clarity.</p></blockquote>
<p>Use <a href="https://www.rimessolides.com">Dictionnaire de rimes</a> for guidance.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Repeated words</strong>: Surround with <code>*bis</code> … <code>*Xbis</code>.</p></li>
</ol>
@doc.content_formatting: <ul>
<li>Ensure consistent use of tabs and columns in spines.</li>
<li>Avoid trailing whitespace unless intentional.</li>
<li>All metadata records (<code>!!!key: value</code>) should have a single space after the colon.</li>
</ul>

@@END:en


